commitResults.messageTitle: Add non-null check to FindCommand constructor
commitResults.messageBody:
The FindCommand constructor does not check if the predicate paramater is
non-null. However, running FindCommand::execute or FindCommand::equals
when the predicate field is null will result in a NullPointerException.
Additionally, many other functions (including constructors) in the base
AB-3 use Objects::requireNonNull for parameter validation.

It is good practice to fail fast. While amending FindCommand is not
necessary to achieve the feature of this branch (which is to find by
tags), it helps to ensure consistency between the two search-related
command classes. Additionally, amending existing classes to fail fast helps
us spot regressions and fix them faster.

Let's add a non-null check using Objects::requireNonNull to FindCommand.

Using Objects::requireNonNull is preferable over using Java's assert
keyword to ensure consistency with base AB-3, which uses
Objects::requireNonNull instead of Java assert for non-null checks.

Refer to this S/O discussion for more information on the reason behind
using Object::requireNonNull:
https://stackoverflow.com/questions/45632920/why-should-one-use-objects-requirenonnull

commitResults.messageTitle: Change tag comparison to be case insensitive
commitResults.messageBody:
Tag comparison via Tag::equals (and Tag::hashCode) is currently
case-sensitive based on the tagName field.

In VolunteeRoll, tags are likely to be used for subjects (such as
Mathematics or English). Thus, it is neither necessary nor helpful for
tags to be case-sensitive.

Let's change the implementation of Tag::equals and Tag::hashCode to make
them case-insensitive.

Existing methods already use the equals() and (indirectly) hashCode()
methods to compare tags. Thus, changing these method implementations is
sufficient.

Regression testing was done to ensure there are no unintended side
effects to the rest of the project.

Constructors for FindByTagCommand and FindComment lack Javadoc header
comments.

Checkstyle raises an error due to the lack of these Javadoc comments.

Let's add Javadoc header comments for the constructors of these two
classes.

For discussion on why the missing Javadoc comment for FindComment::new
only raises a Checkstyle error now and not in AB3, refer to this forum
post:
https://github.com/nus-cs2103-AY2526S1/forum/issues/373

commitResults.messageTitle: Fix missing trailing space in findtag's help message
Update find command to search by substring
commitResults.messageBody:
The find command (not the findtag command) only returns persons whose
full names has a word exactly equal to one of the search keywords
(ignoring case).

Users wanting to search for a long name like "Alexandra" cannot do so
by typing just a substring of that name (such as "Alex"). This goes
against the aim to help fast typers.

Let's change the FindCommand to search by substring rather than exact
word matches.

commitResults.messageTitle: Update findtag to return people who match any tag searched for
Change findtag parser to use ParserUtil#parseTags
commitResults.messageBody:
The FindByTagCommandParser#parse(String) manually parses the tag
arguments provided by the user.

There is already an existing method in ParserUtil that can parse
tags in the user input. Doing so in a different way violates
the Don't Repeat Yourself (DRY) principle.

Let's use ParserUtil#parseTags in the findtag parser class.

commitResults.messageBody:
Per Git blame, this was part of base AB3.

The students testing our product for practical exam dry run (PE-D)
have limited time. They may not be familiar with base AB3's DG.
As such, they may spend time reading these sections on proposed
features while testing. It is more productive for both us and the
testers for them to focus on other aspects of the product with
their limited time.

Let's remove these sections from the base AB3 that none of us edited.

commitResults.messageTitle: Undo renaming of Model and Logic method
commitResults.messageBody:
The methods were renamed in this branch. They are widely used
throughout the codebase.

Renaming them may cause merge conflicts or break functionality when
updating this branch with changes to the 'master' branch.

Let's undo the renaming of these methods.

Handling this before merging 'master' onto this branch so that we
can easily redo naming with IDE's built-in refactoring tools.
